Kafka is a distributed event streaming platform that follows a publish-subscribe model. Producers send messages to topics, which are divided into partitions for scalability. Each partition has a leader and replicas for fault tolerance.
Producers write data to the leader, and it replicates to followers. Based on acknowledgment configuration, Kafka confirms the write.
Consumers read data from partitions using offsets, and within a consumer group, each partition is consumed by only one consumer to ensure parallel processing.
In our project, we use Kafka to stream hold events captured via CDC, ensuring reliable and scalable communication between systems.

