2. How Avro works (Step-by-step)

We create an Avro schema file (.avsc) defining the fields
Using Avro plugin, Java classes are generated at build time
We use those generated classes to create event objects
Kafka producer serializes the object into binary format
Consumer deserializes using the same schema
{
  "type": "record",
  "name": "HoldEvent",
  "namespace": "com.example",
  "fields": [
    {"name": "accountId", "type": "string"},
    {"name": "amount", "type": "double"},
    {"name": "status", "type": "string"}
  ]
}
spring:
  kafka:
    producer:
      key-serializer: org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer
      value-serializer: io.confluent.kafka.serializers.KafkaAvroSerializer
We configure serializer in YAML so that KafkaTemplate knows how to convert Java objects into a format that can be sent over Kafka.
Since we use Avro, we use KafkaAvroSerializer to convert objects into binary format.

memory leaks how to overcome..?
Kafka itself does not usually cause memory leaks, but memory issues can arise due to improper producer or consumer configurations. For example, large message sizes, high batching, or slow consumers can lead to memory pressure.
We can overcome this by tuning producer configurations like batch size and buffer memory, ensuring efficient consumer processing, and monitoring system performance.
In our project, we use Avro for lightweight messages and Cassandra for persistence to avoid memory-related issues
